  "prompt": "Is there a consensus that money laundering is against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, there is a global consensus that money laundering is against the law. Money laundering is universally recognized as a criminal activity because it involves the process of disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. This practice is illegal because it allows criminals to integrate illicit funds into the legitimate financial system, thereby enabling further criminal activity and undermining the integrity of financial institutions.\n\nAlmost all countries have enacted laws and regulations to combat money laundering, and there are also international agreements and organizations dedicated to this issue. For example, the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) is an intergovernmental organization that sets international standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing. Compliance with these standards is expected from member countries, and there are mechanisms in place to monitor and enforce these rules.\n\nFailure to comply with anti-money laundering (AML) laws can result in severe penalties, including hefty fines and imprisonment for individuals involved in such activities. Financial institutions are also required to implement robust AML procedures and report suspicious activities to the authorities. Therefore, the consensus is clear: money laundering is illegal and subject to strict legal consequences worldwide.",
